</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">While she realized she could have ignored the thought that she had misread the screen, she thought that to double check would probably not be a bad idea.<span class="red">AWKWARD!</span></h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">Here see an example of awkward construction resulting from the overuse of the passive voice. </p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">While she realized she could have ignored the thought that she had misread the screen, she thought double checking was not a bad idea.<span class="green">SENTENCE!</span>BETTER!</h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">By replacing the passive verb form "to double check" with the active form "double checking" we relieve the sentence from being overwhelmed by the passive voice, increasing it's clarity.</p>
	<button class="btn btn-large btn-primary example-button">Show Example</button>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">Withdrawal symptoms could be very dangerous and even could be life-threatening, and patients who were experiencing them needed to be monitored closely by their nurses. <span class="red">AWKWARD!</span></h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">This sentence suffers from awkward construction due to overused passive voice and clumsy organization of clauses.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">Withdrawal symptoms could be very dangerous and even life-threatening; nurses need to monitor patients going through withdrawal closely. <span class="green">BETTER!</span></h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">We make our sentence much more readable by removing the redundant words, reducing passive voice, and reorganizing our clauses.</p>
